This is one of the more difficult cases where HTML presentation doesn't sit
well with CSS styling. If you could guarantee that sites didn't mix the two
and always kept the font value between 1 and 7 you could add this to the Resources.CSS file:

font\[size="-2"\] \{font-size:  69.4444%; \}
font\[size="+2"\] \{font-size: 144%; \}
font\[size="-3"\] \{font-size:  57.8704%; \}
font\[size="+3"\] \{font-size: 172.8%; \}
font\[size="-4"\] \{font-size:  48.2253%; \}
font\[size="+4"\] \{font-size: 207.4%; \}
font\[size="-5"\] \{font-size:  40.1876%; \}
font\[size="+5"\] \{font-size: 248.8%; \}
font\[size="-6"\] \{font-size:  33.498%; \}
font\[size="+6"\] \{font-size: 298.5984%; \}

But I suspect you would end up with some very big text in a few cases. On the other hand if &lt;font size="-1"&gt; gives a smaller text I don't see why it shouldn't  make all negative sizes a bit smaller:

/\* Temporary hack to allow relative sizes for font elements \*/
font\[size="-2"\], font\[size="-3"\], font\[size="-4"\], font\[size="-5"\], font\[size="-6"\] \{ font-size: smaller; \}
font\[size="+2"\] , font\[size="+3"\], font\[size="+4"\], font\[size="+5"\], font\[size="+6"\] \{ font-size: larger; \}

